WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.320
Something every teacher knows is no matter how much you prepare, and we just

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:10.960
saw this, things will go wrong. And I had an anecdote, but we'll skip that. You saw

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:17.639
it, right? Things will go wrong. So that means I'm always on a quest to just try

00:00:17.639 --> 00:00:23.840
to simplify, simplify, simplify. How can I think make things simpler, cleaner, more

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.160
streamlined? I mean things will still go wrong, but every like element of

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:32.320
complexity is just an additional point where something goes wrong. And so let's

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.439
think about that in a context of an R-based data science class, which is

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:41.880
essentially what I'm teaching. Data visualization, the students learn how to

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:45.919
think about visualization, but also how to make visualizations, and we use R

